title: London Victoria Station
description:
Main line railway station and London Underground station. This is one of the main railway termini in London, covering the South Coast, Sussex, Surrey and Kent. This includes Brighton and Gatwick airport.  There are also a number of international departures on the Orient Express. 

The origin of the site as two separate stations can be clearly seen from the air, the eastern side for the London, Chatham and Dover Railway and the western side for the London, Brighton and South Coast Railway.

The London Underground station is on the Victoria, District and Circle Lines.

title: Battersea Park Fountains
description:
This large fountain springs into action about once an hour.  It was originally developed when Battersea Park hosted the Festival of Britain pleasure gardens in 1951, and was at the time far larger than it is now. They declined for many years, and eventually stopped working altogether, until Wandsworth Council restored them in 2000 (helped by a grant from the National Lottery).  The 1950s styling, with bold blue and orange colours, is still evident.  A small tea shop has recently been added in the same style next door.

The festival was accompanied by an exhibition of sculptures organised by the Arts Council, also in the park, which included sculpture by Henry Moore and Barbara Hepworth.  Single Form, by Barbara Hepworth, is currently located to the south of the main lake.

title: Royal Avenue
description: This was intended to be the grand drive from Chelsea Hospital to Kensington Palace.   They only built this bit.   The project was one of several abandoned on the death of King Charles II in 1685.  English monarchs never had the funds for grand statements of this type - a fact which may have contributed to the survival of the monarchy.   Houses were built along the street in the early 19th century.
